data.review_text: It's a very famous restaurant in the area, known for the dish that gives the place its name. Because of its fame, it's almost always crowded, so it's common to find a small queue at the entrance.Luckily, the line moved quickly, and we didn't wait long to be seated. The service was good and attentive. We tried the famous Khao Soi: it was tasty, and the ingredients seemed high-quality, but honestly, it wasn't excellent. Given the restaurant's reputation, I was expecting a bit more. It's good, but not the best I've had. They accept card payments.

data.review_text: Tried the Khao Soi Chicken and the Chicken Satay Peanut Sauce Noodle both were amazing. The Khao Soi had rich standard coconut curry broth, crispy noodles on top, and super tender chicken. The balance of spice, creaminess, and a squeeze of lime was just perfect. The Satay Peanut Noodles were such a nice surprise!!!! creamy, nutty, slightly sweet, with grilled chicken that had that smoky flavor 9/10. A great fusion of comfort food and Thai street style. Nice cozy spot with warm Chiang Mai vibes. Perfect for anyone who loves flavorful northern Thai food. Highly recommend adding this place to your food list when youâ€™re in town! Food looks as good as it tastes check the photos that I took here.

Nice cozy spot with warm Chiang Mai vibes. Perfect for anyone who loves flavorful northern Thai food. Highly recommend adding this place to your food list when youâ€™re in town! Food looks as good as it tastes check the photos that I took here.

data.review_text: This restaurant deserves to get its first Michelin star! All the products were not only very tasty, but the products also contained a unique blend of Norhern Thai-style flavors (which are in my opinion the better dishes of Thailand). We felt really treated like kings. The service was impeccable and no waiting thanks to the digital bell on our dining table. As a starter, we ate the soft, creamy and scrumptious eggplant salad, which I can really recommend to vegetarians. Also the chicken skewers with satay sauce was a great addition to our order, with a wink to the original chicken-satay skewers from Indonesia. Even the pickled veggies let me think of the Indonesian dishes for a while. However, I have to confess that I personally prefer an Indonesian-style satay sauce. For our main course we had a great stir-fried chicken dish with a great combination of spices. To add more spice to our dinner, we had the delicious Kang Nor curry dish. I really like this curry for the added bamboo sprouts and dried fish. As a non-pork eater, I obviously chose this fish-variety. However, they also have a pork-variety. My boyfriend and I were seated inside. The restaurant was well climatized and very clean. You could even look through the glass, where you could see the diligent people working hard to make exquisite dishes. Even the dining tables were of another kind of level. At the end of our dinner we realized that we had been sitting on a â€˜remadeâ€™ authentic sewing table. It gives the restaurant so much more atmosphere. As a dessert, I ate colored soft noodles in sweet coconut milk. I must say that this type of dessert, has it all to me. We went to our hotel totally satisfied, joyful and fully fed. I can assure everyone that you will enjoy your meal here to the highest level!

data.review_text: The best Kao Soy Iâ€™ve ever had. The spiciness of the soup was perfectly balancedâ€”neither overpowering nor too mild. data.review_text: What can I say... I think there is a management problem in this restaurant. After being seated, we had to call someone after 15 minutes because no one seemed to want to take our order. No hello. The staff waits for orders with their arms behind their backs against trees or walls. We chose to try the kao soy because we know it well. What a surprise when the dish arrived, we would have said half a portion with say 5 tablespoons of sauce maximum. Also, we decided to try a dessert. Likewise, no one came to ask us if we wanted something... yet many staff were available and we had to call them. And as you can see from the pictures, no one cleared the meal / table before and during dessert. There are other places much better in terms of taste, service and price in Chang Mai.

data.review_text: 1350 for 3 different Kao soy, 2 mixed platters and calamari. Everything was nice enough except the calamari. Kao soy was like a Malaysian curry mee (not laksa) with a thicker and plainer broth. The noodles and crunch is nice though. The silkworms were nice and crispy with a bit of salt flavour. Northern Thai sausage platter was average in textures and taste but the dips made up for it. The chicken satay was nice enough but nothing special. The black rice is like a Bak chang so not a fan. Pork floss and onion ring were quite nice. Pork rind was normal. Calamari batter was not sticking and while crispy lacked flavour. Service was a bit slow when getting the bill. Had to ask 3 different people before we got the bill.

data.review_text: The khao soi here lives up to the hype! My friend took me here, and I was unaware of its reputation. The beef khao soi was my personal favorite, it's so tender and mixes perfectly with the curry. The service is quick and efficient. I really like the button at each table that allows you to call a waiter when you're ready. Our food was served just a few minutes after ordering. As a note, it does seem to get pretty busy on weekends and holidays. If you want to avoid a wait, I'd recommend an early lunch on a weekday.

The beef khao soi was my personal favorite, it's so tender and mixes perfectly with the curry. The service is quick and efficient. I really like the button at each table that allows you to call a waiter when you're ready. Our food was served just a few minutes after ordering. As a note, it does seem to get pretty busy on weekends and holidays. If you want to avoid a wait, I'd recommend an early lunch on a weekday.

data.review_text: Exceptional traditional northern style restaurant with a Michelin guide recommendation. It's both traditional looking and smart and the service is friendly. I ordered the softshell crab Khao soi and the ong pu, grilled paddy crab head butter. Both excellent dishes, well presented and tasted phenomenal. The ong pu in particular was creamy, intense and felt luxurious. Will definitely be back.

data.review_text: Housed in trendy Nimman, this is one of Chiang Maiâ€™s Michelin-picked noodle playground that gives a modern spin to the Northern Thai classic: khao soiâ€”a dish rooted in Lanna history, once brought over by Chinese-Muslim traders, now a Chiang Mai must-eat. Kicked things off with the Octopus Khao Soiâ€”because why be normal when you can have tentacles in your soup? The octopus was chewy, not salty and a little bougie in the best way laying on top of a coconut curry hot tub. Then came the classic hero: the Chicken Khao Soi. A+ comfort food. That broth? Creamy, warm, just the right punch of spice. At some parts, the slurping was wishing the broth had just one more ladle of richness. Ended with a tropical pool party where the Thub Thim Krob came in like a treasure chest disguised as a dessert bowl.Signature ruby water chestnuts (crunchy, chewy, glorious) Grass jelly, cendol, and nata de coco and golden jackfruit pieces all vibing in one icy, sweet coconut milk party. Was definitely pleasing to the eyes but flavour wise went a little under. Stillâ€”worth the visit, especially if youâ€™re khao soi-curious or full-on obsessed with the michelin adventure! Zoom off with a grab-bike ride that gives u more than local vibes ğŸ˜‰

data.review_text: Michelin-rated restaurant. Visited on 28 Feb 2025 at 6pm. High turnover, so donâ€™t have to wait too long. We saw many tourists and some locals having their meal here. Tables were re-purposed from old sewing machines. Eight of us had a bowl of the famous Kao Soy Kai (curry noddlenwith chicken leg), as well as some side dishes to share: steamed herbal beef shank, chicken satay, kai jeow moo sab (minced pork Thai omelette). The Kao Soy Kai is a mixture of crispy noodle and normal yellow noodle. Blended well curiously. The ingredients were fresh, and the meat dishes were cooked well. We also ordered a drink each, and some dessert to share. Disappointed that the mango sticky rice was sold out. Price wise, it is reasonable: total of about 2,800 baht or 350 baht per person.

data.review_text: This bustling Northern Thai eatery delivers a lively, tourist-friendly intro to Kao Soi. The Super Bowl featured an assortment of grilled pork, chicken leg, and squid which offers a creamy, slightly sweet coconut-curry broth with firm egg noodles is approachable for newcomers, though purists might miss traditional depth. Portions are generous, and seating was immediate during our 2pm visit. Donâ€™t skip the aromatic chicken satay skewers - tender white meat with a zesty chili-shallot dip. Highlights include the crab shell roe (tiny but intensely savory) and the peeled coconutâ€”a refreshing, Instagrammable orb in a chilled metal cup. The vibe is energetic, with English menus and swift service, though prices lean higher than local joints. The ambience was pretty with all the overhanging ferns and plants however seated outdoors, there were a little too many flies around for comfort. Small eaters can share the Super Bowl (itâ€™s huge!), skip the crab roe unless craving novelty, and visit mid-afternoon to avoid crowds. Ideal for first-timers seeking a hassle-free Kao Soi experience, but seasoned diners might prefer hole-in-the-wall authenticity. Still, a solid choice for flavorful, filling meals in a vibrant setting.

Overall, it was a fantastic experience, and I highly recommend it.

data.review_text: Will never come back even if I get paid to do so. I had the red curry with chicken. It was very watered down so that even the spice could not save the dish. The chicken was more bone than meat. My boyfriend had a different dish where he had a whole chicken foot just laying in the meal. (See in the picture) Chicken was also more bone than meat and the vegetables were so chewy that you couldnâ€™t really eat them. When we paid our bill and the waiter saw that we gave back two full plates of food he didnâ€™t even ask if anything was wrong with it. To top it all off I had a belly ache the whole night which Iâ€™ve never had before here in Thailand after eating. Two stars and not one because the Passion fruit juice and chicken Sate were good.

data.review_text: Not worth the hype or the very long wait (can be 30 mins plus wait time. Someone actually left while we were waiting and said he had been waiting for too long). The food is good and we enjoyed it especially the grilled beef (though you can get way cheaper and just as tasty at the street food carts) but the Kao Soy was underwhelming. I had the Kao Soy Super Bowl and the prawns (aka shrimp) in it had a papery texture like when you freeze and defrost seafood. Didnâ€™t taste fresh. The chicken drumstick in there was moist but was surprisingly bland and lacked the flavour I have come to expect from northern Thai food. The broth was nice and spicy and overall it was a tasty meal but just not worth the very long wait and the prices (we got 4 dishes and 3 drinks). The best Kao Soy we had was one we made ourselves at Mama Noi Thai Cookery School so definitely try that out if youâ€™re a foodie. Youâ€™ll get delicious food and learn how to make it on your own whilst having a fun experience. If you really want to try the food here then maybe order it to go so you can pick it up later without having to sit around waiting or see if you can order it to be delivered to your accommodation via Grab.

data.review_text: This is a popular place to eat, we arrive 30 minutes early for dinner with friends.. there was a long queue ahead of us, and because one member of our party had a plane to catch, we wanted to avoid being delayed, but as soon as we joined the queue we were shown to a table for 4.. this was because the people ahead of us needed a much larger table together. This was fine, there was no pressure to 'free' the table, we had drinks while we waited.. 1 x beer and 1 x Grass Jelly Juice (A strange drink as it came in a bowl filled with ice and jelly strips that resembles slugs and a dark liquid, but it was quite refreshing - needed both a straw and a spoon). Our friends arrived, and food was ordered.... 3 x Kao Soy Stewed Beef, 1x Kao Soy Poo-Nim ( which is a soft-shelled crab dish), Sai Oua (this is spicy sausage), Kai Satay (chicken on skewers with peanutbutter sauce). More drinks: another Beer, Soda Water and 2 x Passion Fruit Juices. The dishes were delicious.. really good fresh, tasty food. The prices seemed reasonable, we did eat a lot (a dish each and 2 shared dishes plus 1 or 2 drinks each) and the bill came to baht 1275.. that's about baht 320 each. The atmosphere was lively, there was a lot of staff around to help, and they were so polite and efficient. We will be returning to try other dishes on the menu.

data.review_text: Michelin accredited for year 2020 and year 2021. Not afterwards anymore? Crowded with tourists. Decent colorful menu. Both air conditioned indoor seats and outdoor open air seats. Kai Soy tastes just fair and in small portions. Fresh coconut juice is in nice presentation but of unstable quality. Young and soft coconut meat for the first order but old and very hard meat for the second order. There is a service bell on the table. Funny sound of pressing it, lol. Tried a few time but no waiter responded to it. You still have to wave your hands for service. Beware of mosquitoes bites if you sit outside. Bathroom is quite terrible. Dirty sewage everywhere.

data.review_text: Kao Soy Nimman is a must-visit for anyone looking to experience the authentic flavors of Northern Thailand. This charming restaurant delivers the perfect blend of tradition and taste, making it a standout spot for Thai food lovers. The Food Their signature dish, Kao Soy, is a masterpiece. The creamy, curry-like broth is rich with spices, perfectly balanced, and full of depth. The crispy noodles on top add a delightful crunch, while the tender meat melts in your mouth. Every spoonful is packed with the bold, authentic flavors that define Northern Thai cuisine. The Drinks Adding to the experience, drinks are served in traditional Thai-style bowls. This small but thoughtful detail enhances the cultural vibe of the meal, making it feel special and unique. Whether you opt for a Thai iced tea or a refreshing herbal drink, the presentation is sure to impress. Why Visit? â€¢ Authentic Taste: The Kao Soy here truly captures the essence of Northern Thai flavors. â€¢ Unique Presentation: Serving drinks in Thai traditional bowls adds a fun and cultural touch. â€¢ Great Atmosphere: The warm and inviting ambiance makes it a great place for a casual meal or introducing friends to Thai cuisine.

data.review_text: Delicious khao soi at reasonable rates! One bowl costs somewhere around 100 baht & it's very filling with a sufficient quantity of protein! You can also opt for a vegetarian one if you'd like! The curry (broth) of the khao soi is flavorful and is definitely the USP of this restaurant. I also tried their chicken satay which tasted tender and slightly sweet. Great, overall! I visited on a weekday evening and did not see any queues/wait time. Service is quick with efficient & polite waiters!

data.review_text: This restaurant has an amazing Northern Thai menu, but is especially well known for its many choices regarding their speciality dish, Kao Soi. You can order it almost any way that you like, with or without meat. They offer Kao Soi with tofu, mushrooms, or just vegetables for all of us vegetarians. There are other vegetarian options on their menu, also. We really enjoyed the vegetable Thai omelette! Very delicious! Itâ€™s a busy place because it is so popular, so arrive early if you donâ€™t like to wait. Service was very good because every table has a call button for the waiters, and they always respond almost immediately. Prices were very good, too. We will definitely return here and recommend this place to others.

data.review_text: The best khao soi of our trip, thanks to the recommendation from the local massage aunty. Guess it lives up to its Michelin Guide recognition, with a queue forming even before the shop opens. The beef khao soi was especially delicious, with super tender meat. The chicken thigh version was good too, though I preferred the beef. The fried egg with pork was just okay. Coconut was fresh!

This place is quite famous, but I think it's overrated.

data.review_text: Kao Soy Nimman, highlighted in the Michelin Guide, is a notable spot to experience khao soi in Chiang Mai. Michelin recognition attests to its quality and consistent appeal among locals and tourists. Khao soi itself is significant in Chiang Mai and Northern Thailand, known for its coconut-based curry broth, rich spices, and soft-crunchy noodle texture. A unique fusion of Thai and Burmese culinary influences, khao soi is cherished as a warm, hearty dish and has become an iconic part of Chiang Maiâ€™s food culture, symbolizing local heritage and flavor. While itâ€™s tourist-friendly and conveniently located, some visitors feel itâ€™s slightly pricier than local spots nearby. Itâ€™s a recommended stop for travelers looking to try authentic Thai flavors.

data.review_text: Date of Visit: August 22nd This is a famous restaurant in Chiang Mai, selected alongside Khao Soi Mae Sai in the Michelin Bib Gourmand. I visited during lunchtime, but there were plenty of seats, so I could order without waiting. The portion size felt larger than at Khao Soi Mae Sai, the price is a bit higher. If you don't like the strong flavor of curry, this place might be more suitable.

data.review_text: Instagram: @ol_no_nichijoramen Khao Soi Gai - 85 Baht This popular Khao Soi spot is located around the Nimmanhaemin area in Chiang Mai. It's become well-known after being featured in the Michelin Bib Gourmand list. I visited around 4 PM on a Sunday, and since I opted for the terrace seating, there was no wait. Despite Chiang Mai's 38Â°C heat, the fans on the terrace kept things pleasantly cool. I ordered the classic chicken Khao Soi, which arrived with thick boiled noodles topped with crispy fried noodles and cilantro. A separate plate with purple onions, pickled cabbage, and lime was also provided. The soup has a coconut-based Thai curry flavor. Initially mild, it develops a delightful spicy kick as you eat, making it quite addictive. The thick noodles soak up the soup beautifully, making each bite irresistible. The crispy noodles can be enjoyed either plain or dipped in the soup, offering a nice contrast in texture. The bone-in chicken topping was tender and fell apart easily with chopsticks, making it very easy to eat. I added all the purple onions, pickled cabbage, and lime to the soup during the meal, and each addition complemented the soup perfectly, keeping it flavorful and exciting until the very end. I ended up finishing every bit of the soup! data.review_text: We stumbled upon Kao Soy Nimman while taking a walk, drawn in by its charming decor. The restaurant offers plenty of seating both indoors and outdoors. Despite arriving at 4 PM, there were quite a few groups enjoying their meals. It was only later that we realized this place is Michelin-recommendedâ€”a pleasant surprise! We opted to sit outdoors, though indoor seating with air conditioning was available. Despite the hot weather, the standing fans kept the outdoor area comfortably cool. Initially, we planned to just have dessert, but the signature Khao Soi on the menu looked too appealing to resist, so we decided to share a bowl. We're glad we did! The noodles were cooked to perfection, and the Thai lime, onion, and salted vegetables added a unique twist that elevated the dish. For dessert, we ordered two options: the Passion and what I believe is called Chendo (though Iâ€™m not certain of the name). I preferred the Passion drink, which was refreshingly cool, though it wasn't as sour as I expectedâ€”it could have benefited from a stronger passion fruit flavor. The Chendo had a variety of ingredients, but it wasn't as fragrant or flavorful as similar desserts weâ€™ve had back home. Overall, I really enjoyed our visit and would love to return to try more of their dishes. The ambiance, food, and service made for a delightful experience.

data.review_text: Popular place among tourist since the banner at its shop front says it's featured in the Michellin Guide 2020. Price is on the highside by local standard. The Khao Soi was good, though I'm no expert to determine if it's authentic. The chicken satay was surprisingly good, tender and juicy, rather different from the satays you would find in Singapore or Malaysia. The platter of sausage and vegetable is nice, I particularly like the saugage. Dessert is decent too.

The platter of sausage and vegetable is nice, I particularly like the saugage. Dessert is decent too.

data.review_text: This wasn't the best Khao Soi I've had in Chiang Mai; the broth seemed a bit bland. The prices here are quite high compared to other places. Typically, you can get Khao Soi Kai for around 60-70 baht, but here it costs 90 baht. Besides the signature Khao Soi, we ordered several side dishes. The satay chicken skewers were quite good, but the rest were just average. Especially the desserts and ice cream, which we didn't finish. However, the dining environment is nice, one of the few air-conditioned restaurants in Chiang Mai. This place is quite famous, but I think it's overrated.

data.review_text: Yummy Kao Soy and definitely one of the best. Highly recommended for Kao Soy lovers. There were many options, Kao Soy with sai ua, with seafood, chicken and many others. My favourite is the combination of my two favourites in Chiang Mai,Kao Soy and sai ua.. sai is the yummiest pork sausage I have ever tasted. This place also serves great chicken satay with sweet peanut gravy. Really yummy. Also cendol, similar to Malaysian but without red beans, and other condiments. Pretty tasty nevertheless. Highly recommended to sai ua and Kao Soy lovers. Awesome hospitality from the staff and great ambience. Love this spot

data.review_text: Came with my friend but ordered curry mee and spring roll only. When they served the food, they gave us two sets of cutlery without request. The staffs really offered a good service. The food also not bad definitely deserve five stars from us.

data.review_text: Our favorite khao soi in Chiang Maiâ€¦and weâ€™re not the only ones who love this spot, expect about a 30 min wait after grabbing a number from the staff. The restaurant is beautiful, open air, and cool roofing to give it a garden vibe. They obviously specialize in khao soi - we grabbed stewed beef and chicken to compare. Both were creamy and coconuty with a delightful kick of spice, a blend of crunchy and chewy yellow noodles and tender meat (the beef just melts in your mouth) Drinks were refreshing and the Thai sausage was unfortunaly a miss - a bit on the dry side and packed full of spices, I found myself having to wash it down with water constantly. Overall a great experience! :)

data.review_text: We visited this restaurant twice, and both the food and the environment were great! However, by local standards, the pricing was indeed a bit on the higher side. We ordered the Khao Soi Stewed Beef, where the beef absorbed the delicious curry sauce, making it very flavorful, and the noodles were more elastic and chewy compared to others we've had elsewhere. We also tried the Rod Duan (fried bamboo worms), which had no strange taste but were instead filled with a bran-like aroma. We originally wanted to order grilled chicken, but customers at the next table who had ordered grilled chicken/pork/beef recommended we try the grilled beef, which proved to have an excellent flavor. Additionally, we tried the Thai Boiled Wild Mushrooms (Nam Prik Kha Hed Tob), which had a crisp texture and could be dipped in the provided Galangal Chili sauce, though I found that sauce to be a bit too spicy for me. For drinks, we tried Pennywort juice, Gardenia flower juice, and shelled coconut. Each had its unique flavor, but the portion sizes were quite small given the price. We avoided peak hours to escape the crowd and potential wait times, so during our visits, there were more servers than customers. They were all very enthusiastic and patient in introducing us to the dishes, and they responded quickly whenever we had questions or needed to add an order. If your travel budget isnâ€™t too tight, we highly recommend giving this place a try.

data.review_text: Delicious food. The price is on average 150 Bath per meal. The restaurant was included in the Michelin Guide 2020. Khao soi had an excellent taste, the sharpness was just right. The prawns were perfectly fried, and not greasy at all. The sauce for the shrimp was unnecessarily thick. I'm lowering the rating for the service, I waited around 25-30 minutes for the second meal for no reason. When I asked about my order, they brought it within 5 minutes without an apology.

I'm lowering the rating for the service, I waited around 25-30 minutes for the second meal for no reason. When I asked about my order, they brought it within 5 minutes without an apology.

data.review_text: Kao Soy Nimman is a popular restaurant located in the trendy Nimman area of Chiang Mai. The restaurant specializes in Kao Soy, a traditional northern Thai dish that consists of a rich and flavorful curry broth served with tender chicken or beef and crispy noodles. The restaurant's cozy ambiance and friendly service make it a great spot for a casual meal with friends or family. In addition to Kao Soy, the menu also features a variety of other northern Thai dishes, as well as some international options. Overall, Kao Soy Nimman is a great place to enjoy some delicious northern Thai cuisine in a relaxed setting.

data.review_text: Checked out Kao Soy Nimman, a spot that's got a nod from Michelin, so you know it's got some serious creds. True to the hype, the place was packed, with a no-reservations policy meaning you grab a number and hang tight for your turn. Dropped by on a weekday, post-lunch rush around 2pm, and still clocked a 40-minute wait. Went straight for their namesake dish, the Kao Soy. Pretty tasty, though it leaned towards the saltier side - flavor lovers would be into it. The chicken BBQ was alright, nothing to write home about. Price-wise, it's a winner, and the vibe of the restaurant is pretty chill, albeit super busy. They could do with a few more hands on deck, as getting the bill took a bit of effort and a couple of reminders. Was the wait worth it? Depends on your mood and schedule. If you're looking to kill some time and escape the heat, it's not a bad option. But if you're not up for the wait, maybe swing by during off-peak hours.

data.review_text: I'm starting to wonder if a Michelin Star is the kiss of death for a restaurant. It seems like the longer a place has had a star, the worse the quality gets. The food wasn't bad, but I don't think it deserved a star. My wife came here last year and said the food went downhill compared to now. Even my favorite Kow Soi place has decreased in quality after getting a Michelin star. Again, it wasn't bad, but it should've been better. Oh and why tease me with a beautiful picture in the menu of Kow Soi duck if you don't actually serve duck?!?

data.review_text: We were craving for Kao Soy and we found this on Google Maps, never noticed this is a Michelin Restaurant until we reached there then only we knew. I think it's because of peak hour, the staff are all busy to approach us, so we kind of wait for some time for the table and also ordering. We ordered two different types of Kao Soy, the taste is okay but doesn't taste any spicy, we are not sure what the taste is supposed to be because this is our first time having Kao Soy ğŸ˜„ Not to mention, the dessert can taste the ice from the icebox ğŸ˜‚ Again, we are not sure if that is 'normal' tastes? Overall it is okay, will try the other Kao Soy restaurant in future.

data.review_text: there are always a lot of people here, and you need to take a ticket with a waiting number and stand in line. there are seats outside and inside. The atmosphere inside is not very pleasant, since there is a kitchen there, and everyone is fussing around, there is a smell of cooking, and the renovation is not very fresh. Although the environment outside is simple, the plants and fresh air create a more pleasant mood. Keep in mind that many dishes are spicy, especially sausages. I came here 3 times, I like soup with meat. The service varies, sometimes the order is brought quickly, but sometimes you have to remind yourself. once they brought us a plate with a broken edge. Apparently no one is watching this, as well as the napkins and cutlery. If you close your eyes to the small details, then overall itâ€™s delicious. bonus: sale of donuts at the exit of the restaurant, which taste simply wonderful. Unfortunately, they are only sold in sets of 4.

data.review_text: The food was good, the service was good and the atmosphere was great. I had the beef Khao Soi and the chicken satay. My Thai lunch companion was not as impressed as I was ğŸ«¤ Editing my review for a current visit. I do not know what/why the change, but the food was at best mediocre and the service was horrible.

data.review_text: Yo, foodies! If you're in Chiang Mai and your tummy's rumbling for a taste of heaven, Kao Soi Nimman is your next stop. This no-frills gem in the center of town specializes in one thing, and they do it oh-so-right: Khao Soi! Tips for your visit: - Lunchtime gets busy, so plan accordingly. - Cash is king, but they might accept cards too. - Come hungry, portions are generous! - Prepare for a flavor explosion â€“ your taste buds will thank you! P.S. Don't forget to leave some room for their refreshing butterfly pea tea â€“ the perfect cool-down after your curry feast!

Overall, itâ€™s definitely worth coming here for the Khao Soi!

data.review_text: I visited Kao Soy Nimman on a rainy evening and was impressed by the cozy and elegant atmosphere of the restaurant. The place was decorated with wooden furniture, colorful cushions, and lanterns that created a warm and inviting ambiance. The staff was friendly and attentive, and the service was fast and efficient. The menu offered a variety of dishes, but the main attraction was the khao soi, a northern Thai specialty of noodles in a rich and spicy curry broth. but I don't like it very much, because they are a bit salty and fatty for my taste

data.review_text: This place is a culinary gem! Their authentic and flavorful Northern Thai khao soi is a must-try, bursting with aromatic spices and tender meat. The cosy ambience and friendly service make it a delightful dining experience. A top-notch spot for foodies!
data.review_text_translated: This place is a culinary gem! Their authentic and flavorful Northern Thai khao soi is a must-try, bursting with aromatic spices and tender meat. The cosy ambience and friendly service make it a delightful dining experience. A top-notch spot for foodies!

data.review_text: Popular with tourists from South Korea and mainland China. Be prepared to wait 20 - 30 min for a table during weekday lunchtime. The food was all too salty for me personally. The braised pork topping was nice though. Tender and flavourful. Noodle portions are very small for those with single topping. The one with assorted toppings had more noodles. I found the noodles rather soggy but that could be my personal preference (I like my noodles al dente). Soup was alright. Chicken skewers were tender but salty. Dessert with assorted toppings was tasty and refreshing. Outdoor seating can be quite warm. Staff can speak basic English (they could not understand my request not to give me a straw for the dessert)
data.review_text_translated: Popular with tourists from South Korea and mainland China. Be prepared to wait 20 - 30 min for a table during weekday lunchtime. The food was all too salty for me personally. The braised pork topping was nice though. Tender and flavourful. Noodle portions are very small for those with single topping. The one with assorted toppings had more noodles. I found the noodles rather soggy but that could be my personal preference (I like my noodles al dente). Soup was alright. Chicken skewers were tender but salty. Dessert with assorted toppings was tasty and refreshing. Outdoor seating can be quite warm. Staff can speak basic English (they could not understand my request not to give me a straw for the dessert)

data.review_text: This is my second visit to this restaurant, and the taste of their Khao Soi remains just as amazing as it was three years ago. I am thoroughly impressed with the consistency in the flavor. Khao Soi's taste is still delicious, and the best part is that it comes at an affordable price, making it truly a great value for money. The restaurant's Khao Soi brings back nostalgic memories of local cuisine. Their secret recipe has been kept intact, maintaining the authentic flavors of Chiang Mai. The aroma of the broth is rich, and the perfect level of spiciness adds to the irresistible allure of this dish. Apart from Khao Soi, their other dishes are also worth trying. Overall, this restaurant offers a good balance of quality and affordability. The service is friendly and efficient, further enhancing the dining experience. In conclusion, I highly recommend this restaurant once again. If you wish to savor authentic flavors of Chiang Mai, this place is an excellent choice. Their Khao Soi continues to be one of my favorite dishes, offering a delightful combination of taste and value. I look forward to revisiting this delightful eatery.

data.review_text: For Khao Soi with fried pork. The soup is normal. I did not find the special from its taste. The crispy yellow noodles is hard, I put soup into it and waited for a while. The fried pork is very sticky, given just a very very few vegetables (so stinky! ) . Another side dish is fried dumplings, this one is good and nice smell of herbs. The outdoor area have a lot of mosquitoes, the staffs seem to know about this issue but ignorance. So overall, do not recommend.
data.review_text_translated: For Khao Soi with fried pork. The soup is normal. I did not find the special from its taste. The crispy yellow noodles is hard, I put soup into it and waited for a while. The fried pork is very sticky, given just a very very few vegetables (so stinky! ) . Another side dish is fried dumplings, this one is good and nice smell of herbs. The outdoor area have a lot of mosquitoes, the staffs seem to know about this issue but ignorance. So overall, do not recommend.

data.review_text: This restaurant appears to be famous among tourists, I came around 11:30 and was lucky to get inside before people came and started the long line waiting. The Khao Soy is just okay the noodles a bit hard for my taste. The spring rolls are surprisingly better than I expected. The dishes seemed not spicy compared to other places. Also I like the bowl they use for drinks, didn't see anywhere else in Chiangmai. So I think Kao Soy Nimman is a nice option for those who want to try local foods that are adjusted to tourists taste, the location is also a plus, well located close to Onenimman.

data.review_text: First time trying khao soi and this place is one of the best at it. The signature khao soi is really good. We also tried the pork jerky, steamed beef with dipping chilly salt, and mango sticky rice, and all of them was good. Although the price is a bit higher than average, I think it's worth it because the portion is pretty large.

Although the price is a bit higher than average, I think it's worth it because the portion is pretty large.

data.review_text: amazing khao soi, super refreshing drinks (especially the grass jelly), and delicious mango sticky rice! dined here twice during my short visit and was not disappointed. you may have to flag down a server to place an order and get your check. they were quite busy!
data.review_text_translated: amazing khao soi, super refreshing drinks (especially the grass jelly), and delicious mango sticky rice! dined here twice during my short visit and was not disappointed. you may have to flag down a server to place an order and get your check. they were quite busy!

data.review_text: Various northern cuisine. They not just serve Khaosoy but also have other northern dishes. The place is clean and neat with the northern deco style. Giving you warm and cozy vibe. Mix customers both Thai and tourists. Presentation of the foods are good and tasty. Price is alright for what you getting.
data.review_text_translated: Various northern cuisine. They not just serve Khaosoy but also have other northern dishes. The place is clean and neat with the northern deco style. Giving you warm and cozy vibe. Mix customers both Thai and tourists. Presentation of the foods are good and tasty. Price is alright for what you getting.

data.review_text: Plenty of waiters and waitresses and very polite. The food portion may be somewhat small and spicy for westerners but not too pricey. The taste was nice for non-local Thais yet OK for the locals. There were kinds of Thai dessert available. Recommend for a bit early or late meal time to avoid the long line. Parking was limited to sideways. It was nice to try. Recommended.

data.review_text: I would say the stewed beef Kao Soy was delicious as was the pork but the beef had a much better flavor. The pork kao soy could have used another scoop of broth. Initial arrival was a bit clumsy as they were very busy. Only got one menu but worked through that. Took a few minutes to get waited on but after that the food and the appetizers came out real fast. I would recommend this place if you want to try some Kao Soy. The prices were pretty reasonable for what we ordered.

data.review_text: Kao Soy Nimman is one of the uniqueness place serving Khao Soi with plenty of meat to add on for topping. Not only the Khao Soi availble here, they also served the Northern Thaiâ€™s dishes and Thai sweet. The bow of Khao Soi is good with the light soup but intense in aroma of curry paste, the soup is quite sweet not to spicy even adding some chili to it. Khao Soi noodle a bit soft not to tender, deep fried noodle is not crispy. Chicken is tender and hard but the beef is fine. The herbal drinks and Thai sweet are recommended here, very amazing. This is a good place to enjoy the Northern Thai food, if you getting bored of Khao Soi.

data.review_text: A Khao soy shop that produces magic with and without Khao soy dishes. Firstly the Khao Soy is the best one I've tasted in Chiang mai with thicker curry sauce. We further enjoyed the other dishes. Grilled sausage, beef curry, sales vege pork ribs soup, vege and dip and few more! Each one of them delicious. At some corner of the very thick menu lies a picture of the crab brullee. It's like baked uni but for a fraction of the price. Pretty random find but just wow. And a testament to Chiang Mai's culinary standards. Will return!
data.review_text_translated: A Khao soy shop that produces magic with and without Khao soy dishes. Firstly the Khao Soy is the best one I've tasted in Chiang mai with thicker curry sauce. We further enjoyed the other dishes. Grilled sausage, beef curry, sales vege pork ribs soup, vege and dip and few more! Each one of them delicious. At some corner of the very thick menu lies a picture of the crab brullee. It's like baked uni but for a fraction of the price. Pretty random find but just wow. And a testament to Chiang Mai's culinary standards. Will return!

data.review_text: Not a good experience. We are in Chiang Mai in Nimman district for quite some time and only now we went to Kao Soy for the first time. First weird thing is that they close already at 8pm and we were rushed to leave the place as we arrived just after 7pm for s dinner. The searing was very uncomfortable and the service was not very attentive, we had to wave at the waiter multiple times so they finally notice us and we can order the food. The food was probably worst I had in any restaurant in Chiang Mai, maybe we just picked wrong but out of three meals, every one of them was not tasteful at all. The noodles which were supposed to be non spicy were spicy as hell. Not sure, maybe we just picked a wrong day and everything went badly for us.

data.review_text: Kao Soy Nimman is a must visit if you want to try khao soi! They have loads of different khao soiâ€™s to choose from as well as other dishes and desserts. We ordered the khao soi with chicken and pork, both were full of flavor and tasted delicious. They were both a little spicy but it was not too bad with a nice cold drink on the side. We finished our lunch with mango sticky rice.

data.review_text: Decent food with nice decor and seating (AC) which justifies its price point. Service call with a bell on every table but somehow it wasn't as efficient as a simple hand wave. I'd come back for khao soi in the area but would go to Tong Tem Toh instead for other northern cuisine. Recommended: their omelette is very nice. All other food was OK-ish but there are other places with better value nearby. Edit: removed two stars. The second time we visited, service was unsatisfactory and this no longer justifies the prices. It seems like the staff had no idea what to do apart from taking orders and being asked to bring cutlery and food from customers.

data.review_text: An absolutely delicious dining experience. There is a reason why this place was on the Michelin Guide for the Khao Soi it offers. A large selection of various types of Khao Soi are available at this restaurant and after trying both the beef and the big bowl combination I can safely say the soup lives up to the expectations. The restaurant also offers various other Northern Thai dishes such as Sai Oua (Northern Thai Sausage). Definitely worth a visit if in Chiang Mai and near Nimman

The curry broth is the soul and you shall go with the super bowl option if you want to fill up your belly with all the curry noodleğŸ˜ else the normal one is perfect since we are all here to taste as much as food as we canğŸ¤“ highly recommendedğŸ¦‹ PS: remember to get a queue number from the service crew if you seen ppl waiting outside the reception area :)

data.review_text: Tasty beef Khao Soi. Good broth consistency -- taste is reminiscent of Indian Curry. Pickled cabbage, onion, lime garnish is fresh and tasty. Crispy pork with garlic is a tasty side to round out the meal. Wide drink selection. I choose Chrysanthemum tea.
data.review_text_translated: Tasty beef Khao Soi. Good broth consistency -- taste is reminiscent of Indian Curry. Pickled cabbage, onion, lime garnish is fresh and tasty. Crispy pork with garlic is a tasty side to round out the meal. Wide drink selection. I choose Chrysanthemum tea.

data.review_text: Overall experience was okay. Food was just fine in general. Still have to give them the OG-ness to make Khao Soi a mass northern cuisine, but IMO it tastes soso. Service is very professional. Menu is pretty variety, have a lot of northern dishes. Price is reasonable. Convenient location, walkable in the area.
data.review_text_translated: Overall experience was okay. Food was just fine in general. Still have to give them the OG-ness to make Khao Soi a mass northern cuisine, but IMO it tastes soso. Service is very professional. Menu is pretty variety, have a lot of northern dishes. Price is reasonable. Convenient location, walkable in the area.

data.review_text: Large selection of northern Thai dishes and more versions of Khao Soi than Iâ€™ve seen anywhere. Taste was decent although not amazing. Prices are slightly high for the type of food but, then, this is a tourist area. Good job of sticking with the Lanna theme.

data.review_text: Service is fast and clean. The food taste that I did order is quite too spicy. The soup taste spicy, oily, creamy, herbal, a bit sour (put some lime). The herb drink is quite expensive and sweet.

data.review_text: This was a Michelin guide 2020 restaurant recommended to us from a Chiang Mai local. We waited a good 30 minutes but they churn people through the restaurant pretty quickly. The khao soi was absolutely delicious. I got the pork belly Khao soi and the pork belly melts in your mouth. The soup base had lots of herbs and spices with a little bit of curry based influenced. My favorite part was how the noodles were both crispy and soft. Soft for the parts in the soup and crispy for the pieces above it. I loved that combination of textures in this dish. We also got some delicious sides, calamari, chicken satay, and dumplings. All very good. So overall it was totally worth the wait and the prices are fair. Would 100% recommend going here.

Soft for the parts in the soup and crispy for the pieces above it. I loved that combination of textures in this dish. We also got some delicious sides, calamari, chicken satay, and dumplings. All very good. So overall it was totally worth the wait and the prices are fair. Would 100% recommend going here.

data.review_text: Ordered "northern style spicy minced pork salad wrapped in crispy wontons" - they tasted pretty good but there were big chunks of blood cubes, intestines etc in there which I'm not really accustomed to as a westerner, I kind of expected just pork mince meat as opposed to alot of organs.. I also ordered the "northern style pork curry made with peanuts, garlic and ginger" which tasted ok but was quite mild flavoured and watery + half of the curry was fat and skin (again I kind of expected just pork meat - as shown in the picture in their menu). Considering this wasn't a cheap meal, I was overall disappointed in the quality. To make matters worse, I ordered delivery to my hotel and was sent no cutlery so I had to run around to 7-11 to ask for a tiny plastic spoon, made for stirring coffee". Food was cold by the time I got round to opening it up. Dont think i'll be ordering from this place again!

I also ordered the "northern style pork curry made with peanuts, garlic and ginger" which tasted ok but was quite mild flavoured and watery + half of the curry was fat and skin (again I kind of expected just pork meat - as shown in the picture in their menu). data.review_text: Not sure why this place was rated as popular. Service was horrible. After was seated, we wondered if we had to walk to a place to ask for menu. We had to flag one of the many service people around to get the menus. Waited another 10 minutes, flagged down a service person, so we could order foods. Same when we wanted more beers. After 15m12s, we received foods. Khao Soi was okay. Pork curry did not taste curry, was full of fat. Never tasted curry that bad in Thailand. This place would not be my choice again in the future.
